WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.205
Alright, let's break down Congenital
Diphragmatic Hernia,

2
00:00:03.505 --> 00:00:06.405
or CDH, in a way that actually sticks for
boards

3
00:00:06.405 --> 00:00:07.485
and clinical practice.

4
00:00:08.265 --> 00:00:12.284
CDH is a neonatal emergency where there's
a defect in the diaphragm,

5
00:00:12.704 --> 00:00:16.305
most commonly on the left side, allowing
abdominal organs to

6
00:00:16.305 --> 00:00:17.325
move into the chest.

7
00:00:17.465 --> 00:00:20.565
That sounds simple, but the consequences
are severe.

8
00:00:21.045 --> 00:00:25.424
When those organs occupy the thoracic
space, they compress the

9
00:00:25.424 --> 00:00:25.764
developing lungs.

10
00:00:25.764 --> 00:00:29.125
The result is pulmonary hypoplasia,
meaning fewer,

11
00:00:29.524 --> 00:00:32.205
smaller alveoli, and abnormal pulmonary
vasculature.

12
00:00:32.685 --> 00:00:33.604
So what does that lead to?

13
00:00:34.465 --> 00:00:38.724
Two major problems, impaired oxygenation
and persistent pulmonary hypertension of

14
00:00:38.724 --> 00:00:40.145
the newborn, or PPHN.

15
00:00:40.825 --> 00:00:43.825
These babies aren't just struggling to
breathe, they're struggling to

16
00:00:43.825 --> 00:00:46.665
oxygenate because blood is being shunted
away from the lungs.

17
00:00:47.465 --> 00:00:51.084
Clinically, you'll often see severe
respiratory distress immediately after birth.

18
00:00:51.084 --> 00:00:54.125
Look for a scaphoid abdomen, because the
organs aren't in

19
00:00:54.125 --> 00:00:57.325
the abdomen, and decreased or absent
breath sounds on the

20
00:00:57.325 --> 00:00:58.044
affected side.

21
00:00:58.444 --> 00:00:59.404
These are big board clues.

22
00:01:00.025 --> 00:01:01.365
Now here's a critical RT point.

23
00:01:01.965 --> 00:01:03.805
Bag mask ventilation is contraindicated.

24
00:01:04.444 --> 00:01:04.504
Why?

25
00:01:04.684 --> 00:01:07.684
Because you'll push air into the stomach
and intestines, worsening

26
00:01:07.684 --> 00:01:08.385
lung compression.

27
00:01:08.964 --> 00:01:12.444
Instead, immediate endotracheal intubation
is the priority.

28
00:01:13.025 --> 00:01:16.245
Once intubated, management focuses on
gentle ventilation strategies.

29
00:01:16.605 --> 00:01:19.525
We want to avoid barotrauma, because these
lungs are already

30
00:01:19.525 --> 00:01:20.224
underdeveloped.

31
00:01:20.224 --> 00:01:23.485
That often means low pressures, permissive
hypercapnia,

32
00:01:23.745 --> 00:01:24.745
and careful monitoring.

33
00:01:25.444 --> 00:01:29.425
Many of these patients will require
high-frequency ventilation or even ECMO if conventional

34
00:01:29.425 --> 00:01:30.184
support fails.

35
00:01:30.444 --> 00:01:35.205
You'll also see a nasogastric or
orogastric tube placed early for gastric decompression,

36
00:01:35.705 --> 00:01:38.205
another key intervention to reduce
pressure in the thorax.

37
00:01:39.084 --> 00:01:41.625
Surgical repair is necessary, but not
immediately.

38
00:01:42.084 --> 00:01:47.065
The priority is stabilization, especially
managing pulmonary hypertension and oxygenation

39
00:01:47.285 --> 00:01:48.944
before going to the OR.

40
00:01:48.944 --> 00:01:50.705
So here's your board takeaway.

41
00:01:51.485 --> 00:01:54.864
CDH equals pulmonary hypoplasia plus
pulmonary hypertension.

42
00:01:55.684 --> 00:01:58.025
No bag mask ventilation, early intubation,

43
00:01:58.745 --> 00:02:01.925
gentle ventilation, gastric decompression,
and stabilize

44
00:02:01.925 --> 00:02:02.665
before surgery.

45
00:02:03.044 --> 00:02:06.705
If you remember that cause right-pointing
arrow, effect right-

46
00:02:06.705 --> 00:02:08.785
pointing arrow, intervention flow, you'll
not

47
00:02:08.785 --> 00:02:11.904
only pass the exam, you'll manage these
patients safely in

48
00:02:11.904 --> 00:02:12.365
real life.

